\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The power of your words and what James said.\
I\'92m a growing writer.\
I\'92m a growing _______________. \'a0This needs to be in your mouth in the areas that there are alligators. \'a0You\'92re not an addict. \'a0You\'92re a growing ???\
\
\
When I was in high school I was not a good student. I was the kid who didn't study but prayed for a miracle on tests. Homework was almost never done and as a result I didn't get the best grades or even good ones. My only saving grace was that I picked up most subjects pretty easily which allowed me to pass most classes even without reading or doing the work. All my classes except one, English and writing.\'a0 \
\
In high school I skated by on late assignments and rewrites. In college I was no better. My girlfriend, now wife, would proof reread my papers to help but she finally quit, telling me that half the paper was a series of incoherent sentences. My problem was I would write at the speed that I thought of the sentences and sometimes one sentence would just skip to the next one, before I was finished writing the first one. I'm pretty sure the only reason I passed my english class was because the teacher liked me. \
\
From the moment I could type I have always been a terrible writer. I never understood grammar and I'm grateful for spell check because that is a weakness also. When it came to writing anything other than a text message I felt incredible insecurity and frustration. I told myself I didn't need to focus on getting better because I was going to be a computer programer. That didn't work out well for me.\
\
When I went into ministry I convinced myself I needed to be able to speak publicly not write. For the most part this was true, I am mainly judged by what I say not what I write. But there was this tension every time I had to write an email or even post something online. I had other people at the age 36 still proofing my material because I didn't want to look foolish in front of others. \
\
I couldn't write. At least that is what I told myself. It's also what I told others. I would make fun of myself publicly talking about how I can't write and if they ever got a letter or email from me that was coherent and well thought out they should just assume it was written by someone else because it wasn't me.\
\
I would tell people this until one day someone called me out. They asked me if I was praying about my writing ability because I secretly confessed I had wanted to write a book for a long time. When I told them that I indeed was praying about, feeling confident this was the right answer because after all, I'm a pastor. After this admission that I was praying about it they yelled at me (yell is probably a strong word but it felt like it).\
\
They told me that I need to change how I talk publicly what I'm praying for privately. I had never thought about it much. They told me God would not answer a prayer that I was speaking death into. This lead me to James 1. In this chapter James talks a lot about the power of the tongue. If you've never read this book put this one down now and go read it. \
\
But in the first chapter James reminds the power of alignment between what we say and what we believe about our God and ourselves. It says \
\
